Map it! Use map_data() for a coast map and our MUR SST data for the raster. Nice scales in cmocean. Passing expand = FALSE to coord_fixed makes the raster extend to the edge of the plot.

w <- map_data("worldHires", ylim = latitude, xlim = longitude)
ggplot(data = murSST$data, aes(x = lon, y = lat, fill = analysed_sst)) +
    geom_polygon(data = w, aes(x = long, y = lat, group = group), fill = "grey80") +
    geom_raster(interpolate = FALSE) +
    scale_fill_cmocean() +
    # scale_fill_gradientn(colours = cmocean('thermal'), na.value = NA) +
    theme_bw() + ylab("latitude") + xlab("longitude") +
    coord_fixed(1.3, xlim = longitude,  ylim = latitude, expand = FALSE) +
    ggtitle("MUR SST",
            subtitle = time[1])

OK, now a function to get SST for NES-LTER for a given date. Return the latest data if no date given.

plot_LTER_SST <- function(date = "last") {
  latitude = c(39., 42)
  longitude = c(-72., -69.)
  sstInfo <- info('jplMURSST41')
  murSST <- griddap(sstInfo, 
                    latitude = latitude, 
                    longitude = longitude, 
                    time = c(date, date), 
                    fields = 'analysed_sst')
  
  w <- map_data("worldHires", ylim = latitude, xlim = longitude)
  ggplot(data = murSST$data, aes(x = lon, y = lat, fill = analysed_sst)) +
    geom_polygon(data = w, aes(x = long, y = lat, group = group), fill = "grey80") +
    geom_raster(interpolate = FALSE) +
    scale_fill_cmocean() +
    theme_bw() + ylab("latitude") + xlab("longitude") +
    coord_fixed(1.3, xlim = longitude,  ylim = latitude, expand = FALSE) +
    ggtitle("MUR SST",
            subtitle = time)
}

Trying out the plotdap package. Its pretty much a high(er) level wrapper for the stuff above. plotdap can animate plots if the data is a timeseries! Not sure how to include output in Rmd, so setting eval = FALSE.

  sstInfo <- info('jplMURSST41')
  murSST <- griddap(sstInfo, 
                    latitude = latitude, 
                    longitude = longitude, 
                    time = c("2021-11-01", "2021-11-16"), # get data for a range of dates
                    fields = 'analysed_sst')

plotdap(mapTitle = "MUR SST") %>%
    add_griddap(
      murSST, 
      ~analysed_sst, 
      time = identity,
      fill = "thermal",
      animate = TRUE
      ) %>%
    print(landmask = TRUE)
